Superstore Sales Analysis¶

Summary¶

This notebook presents an analysis of a Superstore dataset, containing 9,994 sales transactions from January 2011 to December 2014. The analysis explores sales performance, profitability trends, customer segments, and geographic distributions to identify key business insights and opportunities for optimization.

Dataset Overview¶

Dataset Columns (21 Features)¶

Order Information¶

  • order_id: Unique identifier for each order
  • order_date: Date when the order was placed
  • ship_date: Date when the order was shipped
  • ship_mode: Shipping method (Standard Class, Second Class, First Class, Same Day)

Customer Information¶

  • customer_id: Unique identifier for each customer
  • customer_name: Name of the customer
  • segment: Customer segment (Consumer, Corporate, Home Office)

Geographic Information¶

  • country: The country where the order was placed
  • city: The city where the order was placed
  • state: The state abbreviation
  • postal_code: The postal/ZIP code where the order was placed
  • region: The geographic region (East, West, Central, South)

Product Information¶

  • product_id: Unique product identifier
  • category: Main product category (Furniture, Office Supplies, Technology)
  • sub_category: Detailed product subcategory
  • product_name: Full product name

Financial Metrics¶

  • sales: Revenue generated from the transaction
  • quantity: Number of items sold
  • discount: Discount percentage applied
  • profit: Profit earned from the transaction

Analysis Workflow¶

This notebook follows a structured data science workflow:

  1. Data Loading & Initial Exploration - Import libraries and load the dataset
  2. Data Cleaning & Preprocessing - Handle missing values, standardize formatting
  3. Data Transformation - Convert data types, rename columns for consistency
  4. Outlier Detection & Treatment - Identify and handle extreme values
  5. Descriptive Statistics - Understand data distributions
  6. Time Series Analysis - Analyze sales and profit trends over time
  7. Performance Analysis - Identify top performing segments, regions, and products
  8. Correlation Analysis - Examine relationships between key variables
  9. Feature Engineering - Prepare data for potential modeling

Outlier Treatment Function¶

Implementing Interquartile Range method for outlier capping.

In [11]:
def handle_outliers(df, feature):
    Q1 = df[feature].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[feature].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    upper_fense = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    lower_fense = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    df[feature] = np.where(df[feature] > upper_fense, upper_fense, np.where(df[feature] < lower_fense, lower_fense, df[feature]))
    return df[feature]

Applying Outlier Treatment¶

In [12]:
df['sales'] = handle_outliers(df, 'sales')
df['quantity'] = handle_outliers(df, 'quantity')
df['profit'] = handle_outliers(df, 'profit')

Monthly Sales and Profit Trends¶

  • We calculated the short term 20 day moving average and long term 200 day moving average to identify trends and seasonal patterns in sales and profit over the time period.
  • Because moving averages are lagging indicators, we used the Hurst Cycles method to center the moving averages by shifting them backwards using the formula: .shift(-window_size/2 + 1).
  • Shifting the moving averages helps align them better with the actual data points, making it easier to identify trends and seasonal patterns.
In [15]:
sales_profit_time['sales_ma_20'] = sales_profit_time['sales_sum'].rolling(window=20).mean().shift(-10+1)
sales_profit_time['sales_ma_200'] = sales_profit_time['sales_sum'].rolling(window=200).mean().shift(-100+1)

fig = px.line(sales_profit_time, x='order_date', y='sales_sum', title='Daily Sales with 20-Day Moving Average')
fig.data[0].opacity = 0.3
fig.add_scatter(x=sales_profit_time['order_date'], y=sales_profit_time['sales_ma_20'], 
                mode='lines', name='20-Day MA', line=dict(color='orange', width=2))
fig.add_scatter(x=sales_profit_time['order_date'], y=sales_profit_time['sales_ma_200'], 
                mode='lines', name='200-Day MA', line=dict(color='green', width=4))

fig.update_layout(yaxis_title='Sales', xaxis_title='Order Date')
fig.show()

Daily Sales Trend¶

Insights from the sales time series:

  • Volatility: Daily sales show significant fluctuation
  • Seasonal patterns: Visible peaks suggest seasonal buying behavior.
  • Growth trend: Overall upward trajectory indicates business expansion from 2011-2014
  • Peak periods: Highest sales usually spike during the last quarter of each year.

Business implication: Understanding these patterns enables better inventory management and promotional timing.

  • Seasonal profitability: Peak profit periods align with peak sales periods during the last quarter of each year.

In [ ]:
px.imshow(discount_profit_corr, text_auto=True, aspect="auto", color_continuous_scale='Viridis', title='Correlation Matrix')

Critical Insights from Correlation Matrix:

  1. Discount vs Profit: -0.497 negative correlation

    • Higher discounts reduced profitability

  2. Sales vs Profit: +0.449 (Moderate Positive Correlation)

    • Higher sales generally lead to higher profits
    • However, correlation is not perfect (0.45), suggesting:
    • Also it appears that some transactions do not yield high profits despite high sales

  3. Discount vs Sales: -0.060 (Weak Negative Correlation)

    • Surprising finding: Discounts don't necessarily increase sales
    • This challenges the conventional wisdom that discounts should drive sales

Strategic Recommendation: Current discount strategy may be destroying overall profitability. Discounts reduce profit without meaningfully increasing sales revenue.
